An al Shabaab chief, Moalim Osman Abdi Badil, and three fighters were killed in fighting in Lower Shabelle region on Friday, Somalia&#8217;s information minister said in a statement on Sunday.A U.S. Navy SEAL was killed and two troops wounded in a raid on Friday on an al Shabaab militant compound in what appeared to be the first U.S. combat death in the African country since the 1993 &#8220;Black Hawk Down&#8221; incident.&#8220;On May 5, the Somali national army killed an al Shabaab leader, Moalim Osman Abdi Badil, and three fighters,&#8221; a statement from Somalia s information minister said.&#8221;This will weaken the strength of the terrorists in Lower Shabelle region. It is a victory for the Somali forces and peacemaking.&#8221;The government said the death of the al Shabaab leader &#8220;strengthens the war on terror &#8211; so fighters have a chance to leave al Shabaab.&#8221;A spokesman for al Shabaab was not available for immediate comment.Militants from the al Qaeda-affiliated group al Shabaab have carried out frequent attacks in Mogadishu as they fight to topple Somalia&#8217;s Western-backed government and drive out African Union peacekeeping troops.Somalia has been at war since 1991, when clan-based warlords overthrew dictator Siad Barre and then turned on each other.-Reuters 